ğŸ•“ 3ï¸âƒ£ await â€” Wait for async result

You can only use await inside an async function.

It means:

â€œPause here until the Promise(future value) is done â€” then continue.â€

Example:

async function fetchUser() {
  console.log("Fetching user...");
  const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/user");
  const data = await response.json();
  console.log("User data:", data);
}


fetch() returns a Promise (a future value).

await waits for that Promise to resolve (complete).

The code doesnâ€™t block the browser â€” it just waits inside this function.

ğŸ§  So await makes asynchronous code look like normal synchronous code â€” easier to read and write.

